The Reality of Palestine
nytimes_articles.abstract:
The Palestinian voice has been muffled since the beginning of the Arab-Jewish conflict, and for more than 100 years the Palestinians have never been given the right to speak out for themselves. Their national identity has been negotiated between different parties to the conflict and rendered a moot question at best.  

     Eight years ago, the Palestinians decided that it was time to be heard, and the intifada erupted. Last week, at long last, their "sawt," or voice -- the Arabic word for vote -- became politically audible, for the first time in their  imposed history.

Congress of Quitters
nytimes_articles.abstract:
During a bitter exchange on the Senate floor in April 1850, Henry Foote of Mississippi drew a pistol and advanced on Thomas Hart Benton of Missouri. Senator Benton stood up, allegedly pulled open his shirt and cried out, "Let the assassin fire!" Cooler heads wrestled the gun from Senator Foote's hands and order was restored. 

     Clearly, Congress can be a tough place. Incidents of extreme behavior -- though, thankfully, not this extreme -- have taken place at moments of tension and change throughout American history. So the next time a moderate Congressman  calls it quits, complaining about the "unprecedented" incivility, frustration and polarized extremes on Capitol Hill today, we can take comfort in the historical record: it has always been like this, and this too shall pass. But has it and will it?

Currents;Books for a Cause, and a Cafe, Too
nytimes_articles.abstract:
IF cafe-bookstores work for selling new books, why not for volumes of the pre-read kind? 

      Housing Works, a nonprofit agency that helps people with AIDS and H.I.V., has taken a step in that direction in its recently opened Used Book Cafe in SoHo. With catwalks, spiral stairways and comfy old chairs, it looks like an elegant Edwardian library. The 3,400-square-foot cafe, designed by Benjamin D. Kracauer of Archimuse, sells food and furniture along with the donated books that deluge the Housing Works thrift stores. The shop is at 126 Crosby Street (Prince Street).

nytimes_articles.abstract:
The first duty of the State, President Clinton seemed to say on Tuesday night, is to open up in the morning. After Woodrow Wilson's 14 Points and Franklin Roosevelt's Four Freedoms, we have come down to this: "Let's just open  up!" 

     I thought, with deep shame, is that all I'm cheering for? Certainly I am on the side of the Age of Possibility, when, heaven knows, anything is possible, when even the Government may close.

Currents;Artistry in Paris Under the Arches
nytimes_articles.abstract:
THE historic furniture district of Paris, the area to the east of the Place de la Bastille, is once again buzzing with activity. In the last couple of years, the Viaduc des Arts along the Avenue Daumesmil has become home to more than 30 furniture shops, art galleries and artisan's studios. All are housed beneath the arches of an old railway viaduct that offers cavernous spaces of stone and brick that soar to 21 feet. 

     Proximity to the railroad was once the draw of this area for furniture makers, since the nearby Gare de Lyons was the port of entry for shipments of exotic wood.

wiki_events.headline: Billy Bailey becomes the last person to be hanged in the United States.

pages.title: Billy Bailey
pages.description: American convicted murderer; last person to be hanged in the US
pages.abstract: Billy Bailey was a convicted murderer who was hanged in Delaware in 1996. He became the third person to be hanged in the United States since 1965, and the first person hanged in Delaware in 50 years. As of 2026, he remains the last person to be lawfully executed by hanging in the United States.
